FAQ

Is this really free?
Yes. No trials, no premium tier, no "free for 7 days." Free forever, open source under MIT license.

Is my PDF uploaded to a server?
No. Your PDF is processed entirely in your browser using JavaScript. Zero network requests are made with your file data. The only network request is for dictionary lookups (optional), which sends a single word.

Which browsers work best?
Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge offer the most voices and best speech quality. Firefox and Safari work but have fewer voices and less accurate word tracking.

Can I use this with scanned PDFs?
Scanned PDFs (image-only) cannot be read because they contain no extractable text. The app works best with text-based PDFs. If your PDF has selectable text (you can highlight text in Adobe Reader), it will work.

How many pages can it handle?
The app uses virtualized rendering, so it efficiently handles PDFs with 300+ pages. Only visible pages are rendered at any time.

Does it work offline?
Yes — text-to-speech works completely offline. The only feature requiring internet is the dictionary lookup (right-click word definitions).

Can I adjust the reading speed?
Yes. Choose from 0.5× (half speed, great for learning) to 3× (triple speed, great for skimming). Speed changes take effect immediately, even mid-sentence.

Why does the voice sound robotic?
Voice quality depends on your operating system. Windows 10/11 with Chrome/Edge typically has the best voices. Try different voices in the Voice Picker — some sound much more natural than others. Voices labeled "Online" or "Google" tend to sound best.

Can I use this commercially?
Yes. The MIT license allows commercial use. See LICENSE for details.

